{{Infobox school | image = | name = Coding House | logo = File:Coding House logo.png | logo_size = 150px | location = [[Silicon Valley]], [[California]] | country = [[United States]] | type = [[Private school|Private]] | motto = Change your life | established = 2014 | closed = 2016 | founders = Nicholas James | faculty = | students = | campus = [[urban area|Urban]] | accreditation = None | website = [https://codinghouse.co/ codinghouse.co] }}
'''Coding House''' was a [[coding bootcamp]] in [[Silicon Valley]], [[California]]. The 14-week-long bootcamp taught students [[JavaScript]] and other technologies. Founded in 2014 by Nicholas James, it was ordered shut down in November 2016 by the regulatory agency [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]] (BPPE) for violating [[law of California|California law]] many times. BPPE denied Coding House's licensing application three times and found that Coding House had engaged in [[false advertising]].
==History== ===Foundation=== Coding House was founded in 2014 by Nicholas James.<ref name="McBride2016-12-06">{{cite news |last=McBride |first=Sarah |date=2016-12-06 |title=Want a Job in Silicon Valley? Keep Away From Coding Schools |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2016-12-06/want-a-job-in-silicon-valley-keep-away-from-coding-schools |newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]] |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y5Cftt?url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2016-12-06/want-a-job-in-silicon-valley-keep-away-from-coding-schools |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Based in [[Silicon Valley, California]],<ref name="Hantel2015-05-11">{{cite news |last=Hantel |first=Harry |date=2015-05-11 |title=Learn to Code at These Free Bootcamps |url=https://www.coursereport.com/blog/best-free-bootcamp-options |publisher=Course Report |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y5yQJd?url=https://www.coursereport.com/blog/best-free-bootcamp-options |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> the bootcamp operated in two places in [[Fremont, California]] and then in a place in [[Pleasanton, California]].<ref name="Shotwell2016-11-04">{{cite web |last=Shotwell |first=Elaine |date=2016-11-04 |title=Citation: Assessment of Fine and Order of Abatement. 11/4/2016 |url=http://www.bppe.ca.gov/enforcement/actions/cit_1617026.pdf |publisher=[[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]] |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y6c5GT?url=http://www.bppe.ca.gov/enforcement/actions/cit_1617026.pdf |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Coding House held 14-week-long bootcamps in which students would live on campus while learning the curriculum.<ref name="Crispe2016-02-11">{{cite news |last=Crispe |first=Imogen |date=2016-02-11 |title=Coding Bootcamp Cost Comparison |url=https://www.coursereport.com/blog/coding-bootcamp-cost-comparison-full-stack-immersives |publisher=Course Report |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y7cQXW?url=https://www.coursereport.com/blog/coding-bootcamp-cost-comparison-full-stack-immersives |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The bootcamp cost $6,000 for the live-in costs and 18% of the graduate's initial year of salary.<ref name="Crispe2016-02-11"/> It focused on teaching students [[JavaScript]] and other technologies.<ref name="Hantel2015-05-11"/> In 2014, online lending marketplace [[Upstart (company)|Upstart]] offered loans for students attending bootcamps like Coding House.<ref name="Pender2014-04-24">{{cite news |last=Pender |first=Kathleen |date=2014-04-24 |title=Upstart offers loans for coding boot camps |url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/networth/article/Upstart-offers-loans-for-coding-boot-camps-5425672.php |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y8AQLF?url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/networth/article/Upstart-offers-loans-for-coding-boot-camps-5425672.php |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
In September 2016, Coding House mandated that students sign non-disparagement contracts disallowing them from either publicly or privately criticizing the school. If Coding House determined that students had originated damaging information about it, Coding House vowed to take action against the students.<ref name="McBride2016-12-06"/>
===Shutdown=== The [[California Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education]] (BPPE), which is tasked with regulating California coding schools, declined to add Coding House to its list of approved programs.<ref name="McBride2016-12-06"/> It first warned Coding House in a [[cease and desist]] in January 2014 that it was unlicensed to operate as a coding bootcamp.<ref name="2014-03-10">{{cite news |date=2014-03-10 |title=Editorial: California's coding-camp crackdown |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/california-604718-coding-camps.html |newspaper=[[Orange County Register]] |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y8r4W5?url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/california-604718-coding-camps.html |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> BPPE rejected Coding House's applications in November 2015, in June 2016, and on November 4, 2016. On November 7, 2016, the BPPE levied a $50,000 fine on Coding House founder Nicholas James and mandated that James close the school. BPPE further decreed that Coding House reimburse every single student who had enrolled in the school. Coding House filed an appeal but discontinued classes in the meantime.<ref name="McBride2016-12-06"/>
BPPE shut the school down because it found Coding House had committed many contraventions of [[law of California|California law]].<ref name="Marro2016-12-22">{{cite news |last=Marro |first=Enrico |date=2016-12-22 |title=Coding bootcamp, il sogno di un lavoro da 100mila euro |language=Italian |url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2016-12-21/coding-bootcamp-sogno-un-lavoro-100mila-euro-171600.shtml |newspaper=[[Il Sole 24 Ore]] |accessdate=2016-12-29 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6n6y9IT13?url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/mondo/2016-12-21/coding-bootcamp-sogno-un-lavoro-100mila-euro-171600.shtml |archivedate=2016-12-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> BPPE determined that Coding House had engaged in [[false advertising]]. Coding House said on its website that 95% of its alumni received employment by two months after completing the curriculum and that their average starting salary was $91,000. However, BPPE found that just 57 of Coding House's 70 graduates had provided details about their jobs and salaries. The school had 21 companies in a "Where Our Graduates Work Now" part of its website. However, BPPE determined from an analysis of Coding House's records that just two alumni had been hired by either of the 21 companies. BPPE ruled that Coding House contravened home-occupation permit rules by functioning in residential neighborhoods. BPPE additionally found that at Coding House a male student had [[sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] a female student while people were drinking alcohol.<ref name="McBride2016-12-06"/>
